"Graham A., Gregory-Wodzicki K.M., Wright K.L.","Studies in neotropical paleobotany. XV. A Mio-Pliocene palynoflora from the Eastern Cordillera, Bolivia: Implications for the uplift history of the Central Andes",2001,"American Journal of Botany","88","9",,"1545","1557",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0001543517&partnerID=40&md5=959d9116577ed873c162d56f6afa1819","Department of Biological Sciences, Kent State University, Kent, OH 44242, United States; Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, Palisades, NY 10964-8000, United States","Graham, A., Department of Biological Sciences, Kent State University, Kent, OH 44242, United States; Gregory-Wodzicki, K.M., Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, Palisades, NY 10964-8000, United States; Wright, K.L., Department of Biological Sciences, Kent State University, Kent, OH 44242, United States","An assemblage of 33 fossil pollen and spores, recovered from the 3600-m high Pislepampa locality of E. W. Berry, Eastern Cordillera, Bolivia, adds considerably to our knowledge of three aspects of the region in late Neogene time: (1) the paleovegetation, (2) the paleoclimate, and (3) the paleoelevation of the Central Andes. The plant microfossils recognized are Isoetes, Lycopodium (three types), Cnemidaria, Cyathea (three types), Grammitis, Hymenophyllum, Pteris, trilete fern spores (two types), Danaea, monolete fern spores (four types), Podocarpus, Gramineae, Palmae, Ilex, cf. Oreopanax, Cavanillesia, cf. Pereskia, Compositae (three types), Ericaceae, Tetrorchidium, and unknowns (three types). The diversity of the Compositae suggest that this flora has a maximum age around the Miocene-Pliocene boundary, that is, 6-7 million years. All members of the paleocommunity presently grow in the bosque montano húmedo (cloud forest) along the eastern slope of the Central Andes of Bolivia, which occurs between MATs (mean annual temperatures) of ∼10 ° and 20°C. The Pislepampa flora probably represents the lower limits of this forest because the fossil leaves collected by Berry from the same locality all have entire margins, suggesting that the flora grew near the cloud forest-tropical forest transition. Presently, the lower limit of the cloud forest forest has MATs of ∼20°C, a mean annual precipitation between 1000 and 1500 mm, and that part containing most of the identified genera of fossil pollen is found at elevations ∼1200-1400 m. These conditions are thus inferred for the Pislepampa flora; however, because of the uncertainty of the magnitude of global climate change and of possible changes in the ecological range of plant genera, we estimate an error of at least ±1000 m for the paleoelevation estimate. When the total uplift is corrected for probable amounts of erosionally driven isostatic rebound, the paleoelevation estimate suggests that from one-third to one-half of the uplift of the Eastern Cordillera had occurred by the beginning of the Pliocene. This estimate is consistent with other paleoelevation estimates from the Central Andes.","Bolivia; Central Andes; Mio-Pliocene: paleoelevation; Palynoflora",,,,,,,"Allmendinger, R.W., Jordan, T.E., Kay, S.M., Isacks, B.L., The evolution of the Altiplano-Puna plateau of the central Andes (1997) Annual Reviews of Earth Unit Planetary Science, 25, pp. 139-174; Bailey, I.W., Sinnott, E.W., A botanical index of Cretaceous and Tertiary climates (1915) Science, 41, pp. 831-834; Berry, E.W., Pliocene plants from eastern Bolivia (1922) Johns Hopkins University Studies in Geology, 4, pp. 145-204; Berry, E.W., Late Tertiary plants from Jancocata, Bolivia (1922) Johns Hopkins University Studies in Geology, 4, pp. 205-221; Berry, E.W., The fossil flora of Potosí, Bolivia (1939) Johns Hopkins University Studies in Geology, 13, pp. 9-68; Broccoli, A.J., Manabe, S., Mountains and midaltitude aridity (1997) Tectonic Uplift and Climate Change, pp. 89-121. , W. F. Ruddiman [ed.], Plenum Press, New York, New York, USA; Charri